p0LQEo8RyC3LXib6ylQ2T6cSKgGG0_XRyETeSyhy15556je5gCJ6ZyHxARBGfXS-WKCsZtd1cTvjgRGQmEpFa_0T4llsX-lC202O7coEEVA4a281l66OHVlK37-pp1pfZRKtiI8WEKYXHKwwz7VwpZYM2tUXlxKBiy3noMGX6-MisEXHfCwWacvWRD2iDBuvaD1LALaUg-RD1HcXrDy4y6WtMmL59T1HqE2J4H6wz20U1yTxukFGPJMRKWxldX9brNs1UaoRH1Hk0wMt9gRzPkHurXSNyB9A_SoZSlq0d1KKIZykvc_ndaCD-KxpuoXqoZGsh6P1WLW_QBtP0DZXMd82niwbS62afUtYBEmQ5HHhrvcBy_Ysr5phHpHMyCAyOdxcvfvH4ubbgiwph__2TFTdIpkg5uJlU-NKXSE1NfmkFLHcwfZM82kBg6Ut5DFqMIAearipqcNfYfdGQsJCBjDrW4by6IPKRsBuvJ9BzD4fjJtwMI8Vg06KrUB0PpcJYtRAt__B7Ta3I=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test execution**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether the helper functions should be included after the tests. The developer instructed not to compile or run, which is a relief. There’s a potential concern about untracked metadata, but it seems fine if no metadata is edited. However, I wonder if adding a test that doesn’t hit all the call sites goes against the instruction to refine tests. Should we include more explicit explanations or add a test file with comments? Hm, I’m curious if removing the file would help since it may not meet the required call sites.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring dynamic-access coverage**\\n\\nIt seems that the dynamic-access coverage metric isn't going to improve, as our tests fail to reach uncovered call sites. I’m pondering if it’s impossible to add meaningful tests. The evaluator might expect actual coverage, but I wonder if ReferenceMap being non-serializable complicates matters. Can we somehow trigger private methods using public APIs? There are several options I’ve considered, like using runtime serialization proxies or reflection, but they each have barriers. I'm curious about possibilities around `Externalizable` subclasses too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining serialization options**\\n\\nIf a subclass implements Externalizable, its `writeExternal` method would be called instead; however, ReferenceMap is private and won't work that way. If it only implements Serializable, it seems that class data slots are limited to serializable classes, which doesn't help. I’m considering whether a custom `ObjectOutputStream` subclass could allow me to override `writeObject`. I can create a protected no-arg `ObjectOutputStream` in that subclass to call the override, but unfortunately, it still won't apply to ReferenceMap.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_KHvfRsMH44O0D8X1UlsBFTVs|fc_0b065007e8efcf86016a239d7074688193aaa0453aea861319", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d); curl -L -s -o \"$tmp/lib.jar\" https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/io/sundr/sundr-codegen-velocity-nodeps/0.230.1/sundr-codegen-velocity-nodeps-0.230.1.jar; jdeps -verbose:class \"$tmp/lib.jar\" 2>/dev/null | grep 'commons.collections.ReferenceMap' | head -50", "timeout": 20}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 865, "output": 877, "cacheRead": 27648, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29390, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780718941524, "responseId": "resp_0b065007e8efcf86016a239d5e033081938760314d34f3feb1"}}
